Take of the Pills of Agarick, and Aloephargin,
each two Scruples, with the Syrup of Mugwort;
make four Pills.

When the paage is too narrow, it mot
commonly proceeds from hardnes and drynes;
and therefore you mut ue moitning,
emollient, and relaxing things; as half
Baths, Fomentations, Liniments, and Pearies;
and o the part being relaxed, you
mut put a leaden Pipe, or white Wax fitted
for the purpoe, moitened with Butter,
or ome emollient Oyl, and he mut always
wear it, or at leat a-nights; and a-days;
let a Peary made of Cotten be ued
anointed with Oyntment Marh-mallows,
or the like.

Womens Teticles differ much from Mens, their ituation is within the Body, on each ide two fingers breadth from the bottom of the Womb, to the ides whereof they are knit by a trong Ligament; they are flat on the ides, in their lower part oval; their Superficies is more rugged and unequal, than in thoe of Men, they differ in bignes, according to Age; in thoe newly come to Maturity, they are about half as big as thoe of Men, but in uch as are in Years, they are les and harder, tho' they ometimes grow preternaturally to a vat bignes, for everal Quarts of Liquor has been found contained in them, in a Dropie of the Womb;
they have but one Membrane that encompaes them round; but on their upper ide where the preparing Veels enter them, they are about half way involved in another Membrane that accompanies thoe Veels, and prings from the Peritoneum; when this cover is removed, their ubtance appears whitih, but is wholly different from Mens Teticles; for Mens are compoed of Seminary Veels, which being continued to one another are twenty or thirty Ells long, if they could be drawn out at length without breaking; but Womens do principally conit of a great many Membranes and mall Fibres, looly united to one another; among which there are everal little Bladders full of clear water; the liquor contained in thoe Bladders has been always uppoed by the followers of Hippocrates and Galen, to be Seed tored up in them; but Dr. Harvey and many Learned Phyicians and Anatomits uppoe thee little Bladders to contain nothing of Seed, but that they are truly Eggs, analogous to thoe of Fowl and other Creatures, and that the Teticles o called are not truly o, nor have any uch Office as thoe of Men, but are indeed an Ovarium, wherein thoe Eggs are nourihed by the anguinary Veels dipered through them, and from whence one or more, as they are fecundated by the Man's Seed, eparate,
and are conveyed into the Womb by the Tubae Falopianae: If you boyl thee Eggs their Liquor will have the ame colour, tat, and conitency with the white of Birds Eggs, and they do not want hells, becaue they are ufficiently defended by the Womb. Thee Eggs in Women are commonly about the number of twenty in each Teticle, whereof ome are far les than others.

Mot Authors would have it made on the left ide of the Belly, becaue it is more free from the Liver; but I, ays Mauriceau, think it will be better and more skilfully made jut in the middle of the Belly between the two right Mucles: becaue in this place there is only the coverings, and the white line to cut. To dipatch then with more eae and peed, the Chyrugeon having placed the Woman o, that the Belly may be a little raied; let him take a good harp inciion Knife, very harp on one ide, with which he mut quickly make an Inciion, jut in the
middle of the Belly between the two right Mucles unto the Peritoneum, of the length and extent of the Womb, or thereabouts; after that he mut only peirce the Peritoneum with the point of his Knife, to make an Orifice for one or two of the Fingers of his left hand, into which he mut immediately thrut them to cut it, lifting it up with them, and conducting the Intrument for fear of pricking the Guts, in proportion to the firt inciion of the coverings, which having done, the Womb will oon appear, into which he mut make an Inciion in the ame manner, as he did in the Peritoneum, being careful not to thrut his Intrument at once too far in; having then o opened the VVomb, he mut likewie make an inciion in the Infants Membranes; taking care not to wound it with the Intrument, and then he will oon ee it, and mut immediatly take it out of the burthen, which he mut nimbly eparate from the bottom of the VVomb, and finding it to be yet living, let him praie God for having o bleed and propered his Operation. But the Children o delivered are uually o weak, if not quite dead, as it often happens, that it is hard to know, whether it is alive or dead;
yet one may be confident the Child is living, if by touching the Navel-tring, the Umbilical Arteries are perceived to move, as alo the Heart, by laying the Hand on the Breat, and if it prove o, means mut be ued to fetch it to it self, by pouting ome VVine into the Noe and Mouth, and by warming it, until it begins to tir of it elf.

